/i> (Old English <i>Lēofsige</i>, from <i>lēof</i> ‘dear, beloved’ + <i>sige</i> ‘victory’)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":55,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Livesay was born about 1400, in Livesey, Lancashire, England, his father, Alexander Livesay, was 22 and his mother, Lucinda Doles, was 22. He had at least 2 daughters with Elizabeth Hemery. He died about 1460, in Livesey, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 62."},"et":{"Abt. 1400–abt 1460":"umbes 1400–umbes 1460","1400–1460":"1400–1460","1400–1426":"1400–1426","1426–Female":"1426–Surnud","1428–Female":"1428–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1380–1400":"1380–1400","1426":"1426","aft 1426":"pärast 1426","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","Abt